en_257782_0	At least 42 people have died after drinking contaminated bootleg alcohol in Iran.
en_257782_1	Health ministry spokesman Iraj Harirchi said 16 people had gone blind and 170 had undergone dialysis after trying the tainted drink.
en_257782_2	In the past three weeks, at least 460 people across five provinces have been hospitalised, with the youngest victim a 19-year-old woman.
en_257782_3	Alcohol is illegal in Iran but bootleg booze is widespread.
en_257782_4	However, ethanol is sometimes reportedly replaced with toxic methanol in the contaminated drink.
